      "title": "The Lament for a Man He Had Every Reason Not to Mourn",
      "hook": "David received the news of Saul's death from a messenger who expected a reward — and executed the man for claiming to have killed the Lord's anointed.",
      "teaching": "2 Samuel opens three days after the battle of Jezreel with David still at Ziklag, not knowing what has happened to Saul. An Amalekite arrives with Saul's crown and armlet and a story — apparently fabricated — that he had killed Saul at Saul's own request. His expectation is reward. David's response is one of the most morally and theologically unambiguous moments in the entire David narrative. He executes the man not for killing Israel's king per se, but for the principle the action represents: 'Your blood be on your own head. Your own mouth testified against you when you said, 'I killed the Lord's anointed.'' The anointing is not merely a political appointment; it is a sacred status that David's entire conduct toward Saul has been protecting. This messenger had claimed to violate it. The claim itself was the crime.\n\nDavid's lament in 2 Samuel 1:17-27 — the Song of the Bow, drawn from the Book of Jashar — is the most carefully crafted piece of poetry in the David narrative and one of the greatest elegies in ancient literature. Its opening command — 'A gazelle lies slain on your heights, Israel. How the mighty have fallen!' — establishes the elegiac register. It moves through grief for Saul and Jonathan with remarkable emotional generosity toward Saul. There is no bitterness, no vindication, no 'I told you so.' There is only grief for what was lost — Saul's shield 'no longer rubbed with oil,' Jonathan's love 'more wonderful than that of women.' David weeps for the man who wanted him dead and the friend who loved him best, and he weeps for both with equal public dignity.\n\nDavid's coronation at Hebron in 2 Samuel 2:1-7 is conducted after genuine divine consultation — 'David inquired of the Lord, 'Shall I go up to one of the towns of Judah?' God says yes, and specifies Hebron. David does not seize the moment and march on Jerusalem. He goes where God directs, to the city where the patriarchs are buried, and there the men of Judah anoint him king over the house of Judah. The coronation is simultaneously legitimate and incomplete — he is king of one tribe while eleven tribes are under Ish-Bosheth, the surviving son of Saul.\n\nDavid's message to Jabesh Gilead in 2 Samuel 2:5-7 reveals his political and pastoral instincts at their best. He praises the men who buried Saul, blesses them in the Lord's name, and then — with transparent honesty — tells them that the house of Judah has anointed him. He is not deceiving them. He is commending them for their loyalty to Saul while openly stating his own claim. The invitation is implicit: the same loyalty you showed to the Lord's anointed, you can now show to the Lord's new anointed.\n\nThe battle between Joab's forces and Abner's forces at Gibeon in 2 Samuel 2:12-32 is the beginning of the civil war that will occupy the first section of 2 Samuel. The famous twelve-against-twelve contest that kills all twenty-four participants without resolving anything is a narrative symbol for the entire conflict: the war between the houses of Saul and David will cost lives on both sides without decisive victory until Abner makes his political calculation in chapter 3.",
